# Frontend Project Structure

The frontend mirrors the backend's domain-driven design. The same bounded contexts, the same vocabulary, the same separation between domain logic and presentation.

## Domain Folders

`web-app/app/domain/<domain-name>/` is where business logic lives. Each domain folder can contain:

- `types/` — entities and contracts that mirror backend domain models
- `lib/` — pure client-side rules, calculations, formatters (no I/O)
- `services/` — API fetchers, orchestration, client-side use cases
- `components/` — UI components reused across multiple routes within this domain
- `api-routes/` — action-only route modules for forms (registered in routes.ts)

Domains must not nest another `domain/` or replicate `pages/*/routes/`.

## Page Folders

`web-app/app/pages/<area>/routes/` holds navigation routes. Each route module contains the route component, its loader, and its action. Layouts live alongside their child routes.

## Shared

- `web-app/app/components/` — design system primitives (buttons, cards, tables)
- `web-app/app/lib/` — cross-cutting utilities
- `web-app/app/hooks/` — generic React hooks

## Adding New Features

New domain logic goes in `domain/<name>/`. New pages go in `pages/<area>/routes/`. If a component is used by only one route, keep it in that route's folder. Only promote to `domain/<name>/components/` when reused across multiple routes.
